# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blockade-novel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blockade-novel/blockade-novel] The protagonist is Miklos Bollok, a logging company owner who uses corrupt politicians to clear-fell the last remaining wilderness in Victoria, Australia.
[src:blockade-novel/blockade-novel] He is stymied by a direct action campaign by conservationists.
[src:blockade-novel/blockade-novel] His downfall also comes about by a dark secret that is made public by his wife.
[src:blockade-novel/blockade-novel] Jean Ferguson of the Illawarra Mercury calls it "A passionate and explosive new novel from a great storyteller".
[src:blockade-novel/blockade-novel] Herald Sun's Simon Caterson writes "A well-spun yarn lasting 500 easily digestible pages, Blockade seems destined to repeat the commercial success of his earlier books".
[src:blockade-novel/blockade-novel] Stephen Prickett of the Canberra Times writes "Once set in motion, the action is fast-moving, sometimes funny, sometimes violent, but always compulsively gripping".
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The **conservation movement**, also known as **nature conservation**, is an environmental, social, and political movement, that seeks to manage and protect natural resources, including animal, plant, and other living species as well as their habitat for the future.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Conservationists are concerned with leaving the environment in a better state than the condition they found it in.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Evidence-based conservation seeks to use high quality scientific evidence to make conservation efforts more effective.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The early conservation movement evolved out of necessity to maintain natural resources such as fisheries, wildlife management, water, soil, as well as conservation and sustainable forestry.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The contemporary conservation movement has broadened from the early movement's emphasis on use of sustainable yield of natural resources and preservation of wilderness areas to include preservation of biodiversity.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Some say the conservation movement is part of the broader and more far-reaching environmental movement, while others argue that they differ both in ideology and practice.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The conservation movement can be traced back to John Evelyn's work *Sylva*, which was presented as a paper to the Royal Society in 1662.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Published as a book two years later, it was one of the most highly influential texts on forestry ever published.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Timber resources in England were becoming dangerously depleted at the time, and Evelyn advocated the importance of conserving the forests by managing the rate of depletion and ensuring that the cut down trees get replenished.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The Bishnoi narrate the story of Amrita Devi, a member of the sect who inspired as many as 363 other Bishnois to go to their deaths in protest of the cutting down of Khejri trees on 12 September 1730.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The Maharaja of Jodhpur, Abhay Singh, requiring wood for the construction of a new palace, sent soldiers to cut trees in the village of Khejarli, which was called Jehnad at that time.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Noticing their actions, Amrita Devi hugged a tree in an attempt to stop them.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Her family then adopted the same strategy, as did other local people when the news spread.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] She told the soldiers that she considered their actions to be an insult to her faith and that she was prepared to die to save the trees.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The soldiers did indeed kill her and others until Abhay Singh was informed of what was going on and intervened to stop the massacre.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Some of the 363 Bishnois who were killed protecting the trees were buried in Khejarli, where a simple grave with four pillars was erected.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Every year, in September, i.e., Shukla Dashmi of Bhadrapad (Hindi month) the Bishnois assemble there to commemorate the sacrifice made by their people to preserve the trees.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The field developed during the 18th century, especially in Prussia and France where scientific forestry methods were developed.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] These methods were first applied rigorously in British India from the early 19th century.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The government was interested in the use of forest produce and began managing the forests with measures to reduce the risk of wildfire in order to protect the "household" of nature, as it was then termed.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] This early ecological idea was in order to preserve the growth of delicate teak trees, which was an important resource for the Royal Navy.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Concerns over teak depletion were raised as early as 1799 and 1805 when the Navy was undergoing a massive expansion during the Napoleonic Wars; this pressure led to the first formal conservation Act, which prohibited the felling of small teak trees.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The first forestry officer was appointed in 1806 to regulate and preserve the trees necessary for shipbuilding.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] This promising start received a setback in the 1820s and 30s, when laissez-faire economics and complaints from private landowners brought these early conservation attempts to an end.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In 1837, American poet George Pope Morris published "Woodman, Spare that Tree!", a Romantic poem urging a lumberjack to avoid an oak tree that has sentimental value.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The poem was set to music later that year by Henry Russell.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Lines from the song have been quoted by environmentalists.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Conservation was revived in the mid-19th century, with the first practical application of scientific conservation principles to the forests of India.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Edward Percy Stebbing warned of desertification of India.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The Madras Board of Revenue started local conservation efforts in 1842, headed by Alexander Gibson, a professional botanist who systematically adopted a forest conservation program based on scientific principles.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] This was the first case of state management of forests in the world.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] These local attempts gradually received more attention by the British government as the unregulated felling of trees continued unabated.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In 1850, the British Association in Edinburgh formed a committee to study forest destruction at the behest of Hugh Cleghorn a pioneer in the nascent conservation movement.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] He had become interested in forest conservation in Mysore in 1847 and gave several lectures at the Association on the failure of agriculture in India.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] These lectures influenced the government under Governor-General Lord Dalhousie to introduce the first permanent and large-scale forest conservation program in the world in 1855, a model that soon spread to other colonies, as well the United States.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In the same year, Cleghorn organised the Madras Forest Department and in 1860 the department banned the use shifting cultivation.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Cleghorn's 1861 manual, *The forests and gardens of South India*, became the definitive work on the subject and was widely used by forest assistants in the subcontinent.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In 1861, the Forest Department extended its remit into the Punjab.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Sir Dietrich Brandis, a German forester, joined the British service in 1856 as superintendent of the teak forests of Pegu division in eastern Burma.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] During that time Burma's teak forests were controlled by militant Karen tribals.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] He introduced the "taungya" system, in which Karen villagers provided labor for clearing, planting and weeding teak plantations.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] After seven years in Burma, Brandis was appointed Inspector General of Forests in India, a position he served in for 20 years.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] He formulated new forest legislation and helped establish research and training institutions.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The Imperial Forest School at Dehradun was founded by him.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Germans were prominent in the forestry administration of British India.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] As well as Brandis, Berthold Ribbentrop and Sir William P.D.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Schlich brought new methods to Indian conservation, the latter becoming the Inspector-General in 1883 after Brandis stepped down.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Schlich helped to establish the journal *Indian Forester* in 1874, and became the founding director of the first forestry school in England at Cooper's Hill in 1885.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] He authored the five-volume *Manual of Forestry* (1889–96) on silviculture, forest management, forest protection, and forest utilization, which became the standard and enduring textbook for forestry students.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The American movement received its inspiration from 19th century works that exalted the inherent value of nature, quite apart from human usage.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Author Henry David Thoreau (1817–1862) made key philosophical contributions that exalted nature.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Thoreau was interested in peoples' relationship with nature and studied this by living close to nature in a simple life.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] He published his experiences in the book *Walden,* which argued that people should become intimately close with nature.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The ideas of Sir Brandis, Sir William P.D.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Schenck were also very influential—Gifford Pinchot, the first chief of the USDA Forest Service, relied heavily upon Brandis' advice for introducing professional forest management in the U.S. and on how to structure the Forest Service.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In 1864 Abraham Lincoln established the federally preserved Yosemite, before the first national park was created (Yellowstone National Park).
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Both conservationists and preservationists appeared in political debates during the Progressive Era (the 1890s–early 1920s).
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The debate between conservation and preservation reached its peak in the public debates over the construction of California's Hetch Hetchy dam in Yosemite National Park which supplies the water supply of San Francisco.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] President Roosevelt put conservationist issues high on the national agenda.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] He worked with all the major figures of the movement, especially his chief advisor on the matter, Gifford Pinchot and was deeply committed to conserving natural resources.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] He encouraged the Newlands Reclamation Act of 1902 to promote federal construction of dams to irrigate small farms and placed 230 million acres (360,000 mi2; 930,000 km2) under federal protection.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Roosevelt set aside more federal land for national parks and nature preserves than all of his predecessors combined.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Roosevelt established the United States Forest Service, signed into law the creation of five national parks, and signed the year 1906 Antiquities Act, under which he proclaimed 18 new national monuments.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] He also established the first 51 bird reserves, four game preserves, and 150 national forests, including Shoshone National Forest, the nation's first.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The area of the United States that he placed under public protection totals approximately 230,000,000 acres (930,000 km2).
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Gifford Pinchot had been appointed by McKinley as chief of Division of Forestry in the Department of Agriculture.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In 1905, his department gained control of the national forest reserves.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Pinchot promoted private use (for a fee) under federal supervision.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In 1907, Roosevelt designated 16 million acres (65,000 km2) of new national forests just minutes before a deadline.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In May 1908, Roosevelt sponsored the Conference of Governors held in the White House, with a focus on natural resources and their most efficient use.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Roosevelt delivered the opening address: "Conservation as a National Duty".
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In 1903 Roosevelt toured the Yosemite Valley with John Muir, who had a very different view of conservation, and tried to minimize commercial use of water resources and forests.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Working through the Sierra Club he founded, Muir succeeded in 1905 in having Congress transfer the Mariposa Grove and Yosemite Valley to the federal government.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Theodore Roosevelt's view on conservationism remained dominant for decades; Franklin D.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Roosevelt authorised the building of many large-scale dams and water projects, as well as the expansion of the National Forest System to buy out sub-marginal farms.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In 1937, the Pittman–Robertson Federal Aid in Wildlife Restoration Act was signed into law, providing funding for state agencies to carry out their conservation efforts.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Environmental issues reemerged on the national agenda in 1970, with Republican Richard Nixon playing a major role, especially with his creation of the Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The debates over the public lands and environmental politics played a supporting role in the decline of liberalism and the rise of modern environmentalism.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Although Americans consistently rank environmental issues as "important", polling data indicates that in the voting booth voters rank the environmental issues low relative to other political concerns.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The growth of the Republican party's political power in the inland West (apart from the Pacific coast) was facilitated by the rise of popular opposition to public lands reform.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Successful Democrats in the inland West and Alaska typically take more conservative positions on environmental issues than Democrats from the Coastal states.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In 2019, convivial conservation was an idea proposed by Bram Büscher and Robert Fletcher.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Convivial conservation draws on social movements and concepts like environmental justice and structural change to create a post-capitalist approach to conservation.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Convivial conservation rejects both human-nature dichotomies and capitalistic political economies.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Built on a politics of equity, structural change and environmental justice, convivial conservation is considered a radical theory as it focuses on the structural political-economy of modern nation states and the need to create structural change.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Convivial conservation creates a more integrated approach which reconfigures the nature-human configuration to create a world in which humans are recognized as a part of nature.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The emphasis on nature as for and by humans creates a human responsibility to care for the environment as a way of caring for themselves.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] It also redefines nature as not only being pristine and untouched, but cultivated by humans in everyday formats.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The theory is a long-term process of structural change to move away from capitalist valuation in favor of a system emphasizing everyday and local living.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Convivial conservation creates a nature which includes humans rather than excluding them from the necessity of conservation.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] While other conservation theories integrate some of the elements of convivial conservation, none move away from both dichotomies and capitalist valuation principles.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The early years of the environmental and conservation movements were rooted in the safeguarding of game to support the recreation activities of elite white men, such as sport hunting.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] This led to an economy to support and perpetuate these activities as well as the continued wilderness conservation to support the corporate interests supplying the hunters with the equipment needed for their sport.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Game parks in England and the United States allowed wealthy hunters and fishermen to deplete wildlife, while hunting by Indigenous groups, laborers and the working class, and poor citizens - especially for the express use of sustenance - was vigorously monitored.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Scholars have shown that the establishment of the U.S. national parks, while setting aside land for preservation, was also a continuation of preserving the land for the recreation and enjoyment of elite white hunters and nature enthusiasts.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Recreation in these spaces is and was not available to everyone.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Creation of such recreational spaces involved the dispossession and removal of Native peoples.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Jim Crow segregation laws determined which groups were welcomed in public lands.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] African Americans living in the Jim Crow South were granted almost no access to state parks and limited to segregated spaces that were unequal in size, quality, and location compared to spaces available to white visitors.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] While Theodore Roosevelt was one of the leading activists for the conservation movement in the United States, he also believed that the threats to the natural world were equally threats to white Americans.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Roosevelt and his contemporaries held the belief that the cities, industries and factories that were overtaking the wilderness and threatening the native plants and animals were also consuming and threatening the racial vigor that they believed white Americans held which made them superior.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Roosevelt was a big believer that white male virility depended on wildlife for its vigor, and that, consequently, depleting wildlife would result in a racially weaker nation.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] This lead Roosevelt to support the passing of many immigration restrictions, eugenics legislations and wildlife preservation laws.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] For instance, Roosevelt established the first national parks through the Antiquities Act of 1906 while also endorsing the removal of Indigenous Americans from their tribal lands within the parks.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] This move was promoted and endorsed by other leaders of the conservation movement, including Frederick Law Olmsted, a leading landscape architect, conservationist, and supporter of the national park system, and Gifford Pinchot, a leading eugenicist and conservationist.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Furthering the economic exploitation of the environment and national parks for wealthy whites was the beginning of ecotourism in the parks, which included allowing some Indigenous Americans to remain so that the tourists could get what was to be considered the full "wilderness experience".
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Another long-term supporter, partner, and inspiration to Roosevelt, Madison Grant, was a well known American eugenicist and conservationist.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Grant worked alongside Roosevelt in the American conservation movement and was even secretary and president of the Boone and Crockett Club.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In 1916, Grant published the book *The Passing of the Great Race, or The Racial Basis of European History*, which based its premise on eugenics and outlined a hierarchy of races, with white, "Nordic" men at the top, and all other races below.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The German translation of this book was used by Nazi Germany as the source for many of their beliefs and was even proclaimed by Hitler to be his "Bible".
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] One of the first established conservation agencies in the United States is the National Audubon Society.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Founded in 1905, its priority was to protect and conserve various waterbird species.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] However, the first state-level Audubon group was created in 1896 by Harriet Hemenway and Minna B.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Hall to convince women to refrain from buying hats made with bird feathers- a common practice at the time.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The organization is named after John Audubon, a naturalist and legendary bird painter.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Audubon was also a slaveholder who also included many racist tales in his books.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Despite his views of racial inequality, Audubon did find black and Indigenous people to be scientifically useful, often using their local knowledge in his books and relying on them to collect specimens for him.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The legacies of Roosevelt and Audubon entrenched exclusion into systems of power that shape which groups are involved in conservation today.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In a survey done by Green 2.0, a nonprofit that focuses on diversification, sociologists found that within the NGOs that participated, "88% of staff and 95% of boards were white." This lack of diversity is augmented by barriers that prevent minority groups from equal access to conservation spaces.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Research shows that limited participation in these spaces is largely due to limited socioeconomic resources, cultural factors, and discrimination.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] These barriers are shaped by historical processes, such as redlining and segregation, which confined communities of color to areas with fewer parks, more environmental problems, and less access to outdoor spaces.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] This uneven access helps to explain why many of these conservation spaces are often described as "white spaces".
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] While such barriers to access can limit how much time one spends outdoors, they can also "impair the acquisition of early formative experiences that carry over into adulthood"; this is critical for establishing a meaningful relationship with nature.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Addressing these barriers to access could provide a meaningful solution to diversifying the broader conservation movement.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] New research shows that nature-based recreation could be a promising pathway towards greater involvement with environmental stewardship.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Expanding access to nature, especially for youth, can help increase the likelihood of engagement with the environment to create a more inclusive and diverse conservation movement.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The ideology of the conservation movement in Germany paralleled that of the U.S. and England.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Early German naturalists of the 20th century turned to the wilderness to escape the industrialization of cities.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] However, many of these early conservationists became part of and influenced the Nazi party.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Like elite and influential Americans of the early 20th century, they embraced eugenics and racism and promoted the idea that Nordic people are superior.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Although the conservation movement developed in Europe in the 18th century, Costa Rica as a country has been heralded its champion in the current times.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Costa Rica hosts an astonishing number of species, given its size, having more animal and plant species than the US and Canada combined hosting over 500,000 species of plants and animals.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Despite this, Costa Rica is only 250 miles long and 150 miles wide.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] A widely accepted theory for the origin of this unusual density of species is the free mixing of species from both North and South America occurring on this "inter-oceanic" and "inter-continental" landscape.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Preserving the natural environment of this fragile landscape, therefore, has drawn the attention of many international scholars and scientists.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] SINAC has subdivided the country into various zones depending on the ecological diversity of that region - as seen in figure 1.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The country has used this ecological diversity to its economic advantage in the form of a thriving ecotourism industry, putting its commitment to nature, on display to visitors from across the globe.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The tourism market in Costa Rica is estimated to grow by USD 1.34 billion from 2023 to 2028, growing at a CAGR of 5.76%.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] It is also the only country in the world that generates more than 99% of its electricity from renewable sources, relying on hydropower (72%), wind (13%), geothermal energy (15%), biomass and solar (1%).
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Critics have pointed out however, that in achieving this milestone, the country has built several dams (providing the bulk of its electricity) some of which have negatively impacted indigenous communities as well as the local flora and fauna.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) is an international non-governmental organization founded in 1961, working in the field of the wilderness preservation, and the reduction of human impact on the environment.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] It was formerly named the "World Wildlife Fund", which remains its official name in Canada and the United States.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] WWF is the world's largest conservation organization with over five million supporters worldwide, working in more than 100 countries, supporting around 1,300 conservation and environmental projects.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] They have invested over $1 billion in more than 12,000 conservation initiatives since 1995.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] WWF is a foundation with 55% of funding from individuals and bequests, 19% from government sources (such as the World Bank, DFID, USAID) and 8% from corporations in 2014.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] WWF aims to "stop the degradation of the planet's natural environment and to build a future in which humans live in harmony with nature." The Living Planet Report is published every two years by WWF since 1998; it is based on a Living Planet Index and ecological footprint calculation.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In addition, WWF has launched several notable worldwide campaigns including Earth Hour and Debt-for-Nature Swap, and its current work is organized around these six areas: food, climate, freshwater, wildlife, forests, and oceans.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Institutions such as the WWF have historically been the cause of the displacement and divide between Indigenous populations and the lands they inhabit.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The reason is the organization's historically colonial, paternalistic, and neoliberal approaches to conservation.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Claus, in her article "Drawing the Sea Near: Satoumi and Coral Reef Conservation in Okinawa", expands on this approach, called "conservation far", in which access to lands is open to external foreign entities, such as researchers or tourists, but prohibited to local populations.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The conservation initiatives are therefore taking place "far" away.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] This entity is largely unaware of the customs and values held by those within the territory surrounding nature and their role within it.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In Japan, the town of Shiraho had traditional ways of tending to nature that were lost due to colonization and militarization by the United States.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The return to traditional sustainability practices constituted a "conservation near" approach.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] This engages those near in proximity to the lands in the conservation efforts and holds them accountable for their direct effects on its preservation.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] While conservation-far drills visuals and sight as being the main interaction medium between people and the environment, conservation near includes a hands-on, full sensory experience permitted by conservation-near methodologies.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] An emphasis on observation only stems from a deeper association with intellect and observation.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The alternative to this is more of a bodily or "primitive" consciousness, which is associated with lower-intelligence and people of color.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] A new, integrated approach to conservation is being investigated in recent years by institutions such as WWF.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The socionatural relationships centered on the interactions based in reciprocity and empathy, making conservation efforts being accountable to the local community and ways of life, changing in response to values, ideals, and beliefs of the locals.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Japanese seascapes are often integral to the identity of the residents and includes historical memories and spiritual engagements which need to be recognized and considered.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The involvement of communities gives residents a stake in the issue, leading to a long-term solution which emphasizes sustainable resource usage and the empowerment of the communities.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Conservation efforts are able to take into consideration cultural values rather than the foreign ideals that are often imposed by foreign activists.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Evidence-based conservation is the application of evidence in conservation biology and environmental management actions and policy making.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] It is defined as systematically assessing scientific information from published, peer-reviewed publications and texts, practitioners' experiences, independent expert assessment, and local and indigenous knowledge on a specific conservation topic.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] This includes assessing the current effectiveness of different management interventions, threats and emerging problems and economic factors.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Evidence-based conservation was organized based on the observations that decision making in conservation was based on intuition and or practitioner experience often disregarding other forms of evidence of successes and failures (e.g. scientific information).
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] This has led to costly and poor outcomes.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Evidence-based conservation provides access to information that will support decision making through an evidence-based framework of "what works" in conservation.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The evidence-based approach to conservation is based on evidence-based practice which started in medicine and later spread to nursing, education, psychology and other fields.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] It is part of the larger movement towards evidence-based practices.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Deforestation and overpopulation are issues affecting all regions of the world.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The consequent destruction of wildlife habitat has prompted the creation of conservation groups in other countries, some founded by local hunters who have witnessed declining wildlife populations first hand.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Also, it was highly important for the conservation movement to solve problems of living conditions in the cities and the overpopulation of such places.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The idea of incentive conservation is a modern one but its practice has clearly defended some of the sub Arctic wildernesses and the wildlife in those regions for thousands of years, especially by indigenous peoples such as the Evenk, Yakut, Sami, Inuit and Cree.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The fur trade and hunting by these peoples have preserved these regions for thousands of years.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Ironically, the pressure now upon them comes from non-renewable resources such as oil, sometimes to make synthetic clothing which is advocated as a humane substitute for fur.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] (See Raccoon dog for case study of the conservation of an animal through fur trade.) Similarly, in the case of the beaver, hunting and fur trade were thought to bring about the animal's demise, when in fact they were an integral part of its conservation.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] For many years children's books stated and still do, that the decline in the beaver population was due to the fur trade.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In reality however, the decline in beaver numbers was because of habitat destruction and deforestation, as well as its continued persecution as a pest (it causes flooding).
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In Cree lands, however, where the population valued the animal for meat and fur, it continued to thrive.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The Inuit defend their relationship with the seal in response to outside critics.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The Izoceño-Guaraní of Santa Cruz Department, Bolivia, is a tribe of hunters who were influential in establishing the Capitania del Alto y Bajo Isoso (CABI).
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] CABI promotes economic growth and survival of the Izoceno people while discouraging the rapid destruction of habitat within Bolivia's Gran Chaco.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] They are responsible for the creation of the 34,000 square kilometre Kaa-Iya del Gran Chaco National Park and Integrated Management Area (KINP).
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The KINP protects the most biodiverse portion of the Gran Chaco, an ecoregion shared with Argentina, Paraguay and Brazil.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In 1996, the Wildlife Conservation Society joined forces with CABI to institute wildlife and hunting monitoring programs in 23 Izoceño communities.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The partnership combines traditional beliefs and local knowledge with the political and administrative tools needed to effectively manage habitats.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The programs rely solely on voluntary participation by local hunters who perform self-monitoring techniques and keep records of their hunts.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The information obtained by the hunters participating in the program has provided CABI with important data required to make educated decisions about the use of the land.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Hunters have been willing participants in this program because of pride in their traditional activities, encouragement by their communities and expectations of benefits to the area.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In order to discourage illegal South African hunting parties and ensure future local use and sustainability, indigenous hunters in Botswana began lobbying for and implementing conservation practices in the 1960s.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The Fauna Preservation Society of Ngamiland (FPS) was formed in 1962 by the husband and wife team: Robert Kay and June Kay, environmentalists working in conjunction with the Batawana tribes to preserve wildlife habitat.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] The FPS promotes habitat conservation and provides local education for preservation of wildlife.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Conservation initiatives were met with strong opposition from the Botswana government because of the monies tied to big-game hunting.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] In 1963, BaTawanga Chiefs and tribal hunter/adventurers in conjunction with the FPS founded Moremi National Park and Wildlife Refuge, the first area to be set aside by tribal people rather than governmental forces.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Moremi National Park is home to a variety of wildlife, including lions, giraffes, elephants, buffalo, zebra, cheetahs and antelope, and covers an area of 3,000 square kilometers.
[src:blockade-novel/conservation-movement] Most of the groups involved with establishing this protected land were involved with hunting and were motivated by their personal observations of declining wildlife and habitat.
[src:blockade-novel/derek-hansen] He was born in London, England, and raised in New Zealand.
[src:blockade-novel/derek-hansen] As of 2016, he lives in Sydney, Australia.
[src:blockade-novel/derek-hansen] Hansen's works have been published in the US, United Kingdom, Europe and China.
[src:blockade-novel/derek-hansen] He is married, and has two adult children.
[src:blockade-novel/derek-hansen] He published his first short story at the age of 16 in *The Albertian*, the magazine of his secondary school, Mount Albert Grammar School.
[src:blockade-novel/derek-hansen] At age 20 Hansen moved to London to work for J.
[src:blockade-novel/derek-hansen] Walter Thompson, and went on to run his own advertising agency.
[src:blockade-novel/derek-hansen] After twenty years, he sold his ad agency and wrote *Lunch with the Generals*.
[src:blockade-novel/derek-hansen] Hansen's most popular book, *Sole Survivor*, had gone through 17 printings by 2005.
[src:blockade-novel/derek-hansen] Tim Pankhurst, editor of *The Press*, says of Hansen's fishing books, which draws on his New Zealand childhood and passion for fishing: "Hansen's fishing books are the ones that get away.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Direct action may include activities that can be either violent or nonviolent, targeting people, groups, institutions, actions, or property that its participants deem objectionable.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Violent direct action may include political violence such as assault, murder including assassination, violent strikes, sabotage, property destruction, and rioting.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Nonviolent direct action may include peaceful demonstrations, civil disobedience, sit-ins, peaceful strikes, and counter-economics.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] It is not known when the term *direct action* first appeared.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Spanish philosopher José Ortega y Gasset wrote that the term and concept of direct action originated in *fin de siècle* France.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] The Industrial Workers of the World union first mentioned the term "direct action" in a publication about the 1910 Chicago strike.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] In his 1920 book *Direct Action*, William Mellor categorized direct action with the struggle between worker and employer for economic control.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Mellor defined it "as the use of some form of economic power for securing of ends desired by those who possess that power." He considered it a tool of both owners and workers, and for this reason he included lockouts and cartels, as well as strikes and sabotage.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Canadian anarchist Ann Hansen, one of the Squamish Five, wrote in her book *Direct Action* that "the essence of direct action [...] is people fighting for themselves, rejecting those who claim to represent their true interests, whether they be revolutionaries or government officials".
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Anti-globalization activists forced the Seattle WTO Ministerial Conference of 1999 to end early via direct action tactics and prefigurative politics.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] On April 28, 2009, Greenpeace activists, including Phil Radford, scaled a crane across the street from the Department of State, calling on world leaders to address climate change.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Soon thereafter, they dropped a banner from Mount Rushmore, placing President Obama's face next to other historic presidents.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] The banner read: "History honors leaders.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Human rights activists have used direct action in the campaign to close the School of the Americas (SOA).
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] 245 SOA Watch protestors have collectively spent almost 100 years in prison, and more than 50 people have served probation sentences.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] In the United States, direct action is increasingly used to oppose the fossil fuel industry, oil drilling, pipelines, and gas power plant projects.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Direct action was taken at arms factories in the United States and the United Kingdom that supplied arms to Israel during the Gaza war.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Anarchists organize almost exclusively through direct action, which they use due to a rejection of party politics and a refusal to work within hierarchical bureaucratic institutions.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Some protestors dress in black bloc, wearing black clothing and face coverings to obscure their identities.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Ende Gelände protestors wear matching white suits.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] One of Greenpeace's tactics is to install banners in trees or at symbolic places like offices, statues, and nuclear power plants.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Direct action protestors may also destroy property through actions such as vandalism, theft, breaking and entering, sabotage, tree spiking, arson, bombing, ecotage, or eco-terrorism.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Pranks may also be considered a form of direct action.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Examples of direct action pranks include the use of stink, critter, and paint bombs.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] The Yes Men practice nonviolent direct action through pranks.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Some direct action groups form legal teams, addressing interactions with law enforcement, judges, and courts.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Definitions of what constitutes violent or nonviolent direct action vary.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Sociologist Dieter Rucht states that determining if an act is violent falls along a spectrum or gradient—lesser property damage is not violence, injuries to humans are violent, and acts in between could be labelled either way depending on the circumstances.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Rucht states that definitions of "violence" vary widely, and cultural perspectives can also color such labels.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Some activist groups, such as Earth Liberation Front and Animal Liberation Front, use property destruction, arson, and sabotage and claim their acts are nonviolent as they believe that violence is harm directed toward living things.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] American civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr., who used direct action tactics such as boycotts, felt that the goal of nonviolent direct action was to "create such a crisis and foster such a tension" as to demand a response.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Mahatma Gandhi's methods, which he called *satyagraha*, did not involve confrontation and could be described as "removal of support" without breaking laws besides those explicitly targeted.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Examples of targeted laws include the salt tax and the Asiatic Registration Act.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Other terms for nonviolent direct action include civil resistance, people power, and positive action.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Insurrectionary anarchism, a militant variant of anarchist ideology, primarily deals with direct action against governments.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Insurrectionist anarchists see countries as inherently controlled by the upper classes, and thereby impossible to reform.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] While the vast majority of anarchists are not militant and do not engage in militant actions, insurrectionists take violent action against the state and other targets.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Most insurrectionary anarchists largely reject mass grassroots organizations created by other anarchists, instead calling for coordinated militant action to be taken by decentralized cell networks.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] Fascism emphasizes direct action, including the legitimization of political violence, as a core part of its politics.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] While radical activism has been effective as part of the civil rights movement, forceful or violent environmental sabotage (FVES) can have a "negative impact on voter attitudes toward all environmental organizations", though that effect is contingent on the organizations' prior record.
[src:blockade-novel/direct-action] In polls conducted in the United Kingdom, two-thirds of respondents supported non-violent environmental direct action, while a similar percentage believed defacing art or public monuments should be criminalized.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The company's name is derived from a combination of the firm's predecessors.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Harper & Brothers, founded in 1817 in New York, merged with Row, Peterson & Company in 1962 to form Harper & Row, which was acquired by News Corp in 1987.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The Scottish publishing company William Collins, Sons, founded in 1819 in Glasgow, was acquired by News Corp in 1987 and merged with Harper & Row to form HarperCollins.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The logo for the firm combines the fire from Harper's torch and the water from Collins' fountain.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperCollins operates publishing groups in the United States, Canada, the United Kingdom, Australia, New Zealand, Brazil, India, and China, and publishes under various imprints.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Brian Murray has served as the company's president and chief executive since 2008.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The earliest of the publishing firms that comprise HarperCollins was founded in 1817 by James Harper and his brother John, initially operating under the name J & J Harper.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] They were later joined by two other brothers, Joseph Wesley and Fletcher Harper, with the firm becoming Harper & Brothers in 1833.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Harper & Brothers originated several notable magazine publications in the nineteenth century that would later be sold or discontinued, including *Harper's Magazine*, *Harper's Weekly*, *Harper's Bazaar*, and *Harper's Young People*.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In 1962, Harper & Brothers merged with Row, Peterson & Company to become Harper & Row.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Lippincott & Co. in the 1970s, with Crowell and the trade operations of Lippincott merged into Harper & Row in 1980.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In 1988, Harper & Row purchased the religious publisher Zondervan, including subsidiary Marshall Pickering.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] William Collins, Sons was established in Glasgow in 1819 by Presbyterian schoolmaster William Collins.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The firm's early emphasis was on religion and education, but diversified over time, making a significant move into fiction in 1917 under the leadership of Godfrey Collins.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The Collins Crime Club imprint published many works in the Golden Age of Detective Fiction, including novels by Agatha Christie and Rex Stout.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The religious imprint Fount would be home to C.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Collins would become the British Commonwealth publisher for a number of popular American juvenile series and authors, including The Hardy Boys, Nancy Drew, and Dr.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In November 2024, HarperCollins signed a licensing agreement with Microsoft to provide book content for training generative AI models, becoming the first major book publisher to do so.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation acquired Harper & Row in March 1987.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] News Corp had owned a 40% stake in Collins since 1981 and became the sole owner in 1989.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] News Corp merged the two publishers in 1989, combining the name as HarperCollins and creating a logo with a stylized depiction of flames atop waves derived from the torch logo for Harper & Row and the fountain logo for Collins.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Lippincott & Co., its medical publishing division, to the Dutch publisher Wolters Kluwer.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In 1996, HarperCollins sold Scott Foresman and HarperCollins College to Pearson, which merged them with Addison-Wesley Longman.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] News Corporation purchased the Hearst Book Group, consisting of William Morrow & Company and Avon Books, in 1999.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] These imprints are now published under the rubric of HarperCollins.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperCollins bought educational publisher Letts and Lonsdale in March 2010.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In 2011, HarperCollins announced they had agreed to acquire the publisher Thomas Nelson.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The purchase was completed on 11 July 2012, with an announcement that Thomas Nelson would operate independently given the position it has in Christian book publishing.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Both Thomas Nelson and Zondervan were then organized as imprints, or "keystone publishing programs," under a new division, HarperCollins Christian Publishing.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Key roles in the reorganization were awarded to former Thomas Nelson executives.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In 2012, HarperCollins acquired part of the trade operations of John Wiley & Son in Canada.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In 2014, HarperCollins acquired Canadian romance publisher Harlequin Enterprises for C$455 million.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In 2018, HarperCollins acquired the business publisher Amacom from the American Management Association.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In 2020, HarperCollins acquired the children's publishers Egmont Books UK, Egmont Poland and Schneiderbuch Germany from the Egmont Group.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] On 29 March 2021, HarperCollins announced that it would acquire HMH Books & Media, the trade publishing division of Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, for $349 million.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The deal would allow HMH to pay down its debt and focus on digital education.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] As of 7 July 2021, HMH's adult books will be published as Mariner Books, while HMH's children's books will be published as Clarion Books.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In 2021, HarperCollins acquired the British publisher Pavilion Books.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In 2022, HarperCollins acquired Cider Mill Press.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] On 16 July 2025, HarperCollins announced that it has acquired the French and German Crunchyroll manga publishing business, with the acquisition being closed on 30 September 2025.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Brian Murray, the current CEO of HarperCollins, succeeded Jane Friedman who was chief executive from 1997 to 2008.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Notable management figures include Lisa Sharkey, current senior vice president and director of creative development and Barry Winkleman from 1989 to 1994.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In October 2025, the company appointed Kate Elton as its UK and Ireland interim chief executive following Charlie Redmayne's resignation.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In April 2012, the United States Department of Justice filed *United States v.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Apple Inc.*, naming Apple, HarperCollins, and four other major publishers as defendants.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The suit alleged that they conspired to fix prices for e-books, and weaken Amazon.com's position in the market, in violation of antitrust law.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In December 2013, a federal judge approved a settlement of the antitrust claims, in which HarperCollins and the other publishers paid into a fund that provided credits to customers who had overpaid for books due to the price-fixing.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] On 5 November 2012, HarperCollins announced to employees privately and then later in the day publicly that it was closing its remaining two US warehouses, to merge shipping and warehousing operations with R.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The Scranton, Pennsylvania, warehouse closed in September 2013 and a Nashville, Tennessee, warehouse, under the name Thomas Nelson (which distributes the religious arm of HarperCollins/Zondervan Books), in the winter of 2013.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Several office positions and departments continued to work for HarperCollins in Scranton, but in a new location.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The Scranton warehouse closing eliminated about 200 jobs, and the Nashville warehouse closing eliminated up to 500 jobs; the exact number of distribution employees is unknown.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperCollins previously closed two US warehouses, one in Williamsport, Pennsylvania, in 2011 and another in Grand Rapids, Michigan, in 2012.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] "We have taken a long-term, global view of our print distribution and are committed to offering the broadest possible reach for our authors," said HarperCollins Chief Executive Brian Murray, according to *Publishers Weekly*.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] "We are retooling the traditional distribution model to ensure we can competitively offer the entire HarperCollins catalog to customers regardless of location." Company officials attribute the closings and mergers to the rapidly growing demand for e-book formats and the decline in print purchasing.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In June 2020, HarperCollins was one of a group of publishers who sued the Internet Archive, arguing that its collection of e-books was denying authors and publishers revenue and accusing the library of "willful mass copyright infringement".
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In September 2020, HarperCollins sued Lindsay Lohan for entering into a book deal and collecting a $350,000 advance for a tell-all memoir that never materialized.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] A 2022 book written by Rosemary Sullivan, with HarperCollins as main publisher, designated Jewish notary Arnold van den Bergh as the most likely suspect in Anne Frank's betrayal.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The conclusion was challenged by experts.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The notary's family members threatened a lawsuit and started a foundation.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The Dutch publisher withdrew the book, but HarperCollins has not taken any definitive decision.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] On 10 November 2022, approximately 250 unionized workers at HarperCollins began an indefinite strike.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Local 2110 of the United Auto Workers (UAW) union includes people in design, marketing, publicity, and sales for the company.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] On 21 December 2022 the local put their in-person picketing on "pause" to give strikers an opportunity to spend time with their loved ones.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The picketing resumed as scheduled on 3 January 2023.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] After three months of negotiations, the union agreed to a new contract with HarperCollins on 16 February 2023.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Under the new terms, the annual starting pay of HarperCollins employees has increased from $45,000 to $47,500 upon ratification, and is set to rise to $50,000 by 2025.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Additionally, full-time employees in the union will receive a lump sum payment of $1,500.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The contract also allows workers making less than $60,000 to file for two hours of overtime pay per week without approval from a manager, and puts measures in place to compensate junior-level staff for diversity and inclusion work which is typically unpaid in the industry.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The workers returned to their duties on 21 February.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperCollins maintains the backlist of many of the books originally published by its many merged imprints, in addition to having picked up new authors since the merger.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Authors published originally by Harper include Mark Twain, the Brontë sisters, and William Makepeace Thackeray.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Authors published originally by Collins include H.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperCollins also acquired the publishing rights to J.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Tolkien's work in 1990 when Unwin Hyman was bought.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Following is a list of some of the more noted books and series published by HarperCollins and their various imprints and merged publishing houses.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] They were the publishing home of Maurice Sendak, Shel Silverstein, and Margaret Wise Brown.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In 1998, Nordstrom's personal correspondence was published as *Dear Genius: The Letters of Ursula Nordstrom* (illustrated by Maurice Sendak), edited by Charlotte Zolotow.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Zolotow began her career as a stenographer to Nordstrom, became her *protégé*, and went on to write more than 80 books and edit hundreds of others, including Nordstrom's *The Secret Language* and the works of Paul Fleischman.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Zolotow later became head of the children's books department, and went on to become the company's first female vice president.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperCollins has more than 120 book imprints, most of which are based in the United States.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Collins still exists as an imprint, chiefly for wildlife and natural history books, field guides, as well as for English and bilingual dictionaries based on the Bank of English, a large corpus of contemporary English texts.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In 2008, HarperCollins launched a browsing feature on its website where customers can read selected excerpts from books before purchasing, on both desktop and mobile browsers.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] This functionality gave the publisher's website the ability to compete with physical bookstores, in which customers can typically look at the book itself, and Amazon's use of excerpts ("teasers") for online book purchasers.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] At the beginning of October 2013, the company announced a partnership with online digital library Scribd.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The official statement revealed that the "majority" of the HarperCollins US and HarperCollins Christian catalogs will be available in Scribd's subscription service.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Chantal Restivo-Alessi, chief digital officer at HarperCollins, explained to the media that the deal represents the first time that the publisher has released such a large portion of its catalog.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperCollins formerly operated *authonomy*, an online community of authors, from 2008 to 2015.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The website offered an alternative to the traditional "slush pile" approach for handling unsolicited manuscripts sent to a publisher with little chance of being reviewed.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Using authonomy, authors could submit their work for peer review and ranking by other members; the five highest-ranked manuscripts each month would be read by HarperCollins editors for potential publication.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The site was closed after authors "learned to game the system" to earn top-five rankings, and fewer authonomy titles were selected to be published.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] From 2009 to 2010, HarperCollins operated BookArmy, a social networking site.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The **HarperCollins Speakers Bureau** (also known as HCSB) is the first lecture agency to be created by a major publishing house.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] It was launched in May 2005 as a division of HarperCollins to book paid speaking engagements for the authors HarperCollins, and its sister companies, publish.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Some of the notable authors the HCSB represents include Carol Alt, Dennis Lehane, Gregory Maguire, Danny Meyer, Mehmet Oz, Sidney Poitier, Ted Sorensen, and Kate White.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperAcademic is the academic marketing department of HarperCollins.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperAcademic provides instructors with the latest in adult titles for course adoption at the high school and college level, as well as titles for first-year and other common read programs at academic institutions.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] They also attend several major academic conferences to showcase new titles for academic professionals.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperAcademic Calling, a podcast produced by the department, provides interviews with authors of noteworthy titles.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperCollins announced HarperStudio in 2008 as a "new, experimental unit... that will eliminate the traditional profit distributions to authors.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The long-established author advances and bookseller returns has not proved to be very profitable to either the author or the publisher.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperStudio folded in March 2010 after Miller left for Workman Publishing.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperCollins Publishers India Pvt Ltd. is a wholly owned subsidiary of HarperCollins Worldwide.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In August 2010, the company became embroiled in a legal battle with the BBC after a book it was due to publish, later identified as the forthcoming autobiography of racing driver Ben Collins (no relation to the publishers), revealed the identity of The Stig from *Top Gear*.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In his blog, *Top Gear* executive producer Andy Wilman accused HarperCollins of "hoping to cash in" on the BBC's intellectual property, describing the publishers as "a bunch of chancers".
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] On 1 September, the BBC's request for an injunction preventing the book from being published was turned down, effectively confirming the book's revelation that "The Stig" was indeed Collins.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The company became embroiled in controversy in 1998 after it was revealed it blocked Chris Patten's (the last British governor of Hong Kong) book *East and West* after a direct intervention by the then-CEO of News International, Rupert Murdoch.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Murdoch's intervention caused both Proffitt's resignation from the company and outrage from the international media apart from affiliated companies.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] Chris Patten later published with Macmillan Publishing, initially in America, where it carried the logo "The book that Rupert Murdoch refused to publish".
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] After a successful legal campaign against HarperCollins, Patten went on to publish the book in the UK in September 1998 after accepting a sum of £500,000 and receiving an apology from Rupert Murdoch.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In March 2011, HarperCollins announced it would distribute ebooks to libraries with DRM enabled to delete the item after being lent 26 times.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperCollins has drawn criticism of this plan, in particular its likening of ebooks, which are purely digital, to traditional paperback trade books, which wear over time.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] In December 2014, *The Tablet* reported that an atlas published for Middle East schools did not label Israel on a map of the Middle East.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] A representative for Collins Bartholomew, a subsidiary of HarperCollins that specializes in maps, explained that including Israel would have been "unacceptable" to their customers in the Arab states of the Persian Gulf and the omission was in line with "local preferences".
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The company later apologized and destroyed all the books.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] HarperCollins announced in January 2017 that they would discontinue selling copies of Monica Crowley's book *What the (Bleep) Just Happened?*, due to allegations of plagiarism.
[src:blockade-novel/harpercollins] The 2012 book had lifted passages from a number of sources including columns, news articles and think tank reports.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Land clearing remains a significant environmental issue in Australia.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Conservation and government reports estimate that approximately 500,000 hectares of native vegetation are cleared each year, mainly for pasture expansion in Queensland and New South Wales.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] The Brigalow Belt and Mulga Lands are among the regions with the highest recent rates of clearing.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Eastern Australia is considered one of the world's global deforestation hotspots, with rates of vegetation loss comparable to tropical regions such as the Amazon.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Recent studies link large-scale clearing to habitat loss, greenhouse gas emissions, and declines in biodiversity, particularly affecting species such as koalas and greater gliders.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Land clearing is regulated primarily at the state level.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Queensland and New South Wales have introduced laws to limit or monitor clearing.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Despite these measures, satellite data and environmental assessments indicate that unregulated and secondary clearing continue across parts of the country.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Land clearing in Australia began soon after European settlement, when forests and bushlands were removed to create farmland and settlements.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Historically, the rural sector was viewed as an important piece of the economic fabric of Australia.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Throughout the 19th and 20th centuries, governments encouraged clearing through land grants and subsidies, viewing it as a means of increasing productivity and contributing to national progress.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Throughout the mid to late twentieth century, land clearing continued to be associated mostly with agricultural expansion.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Technological advancements further reduced the cost and effort required to clear the land, which led to more wide-scale clearing projects at a faster rate.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Clearing in the twentieth century was also heavily influenced by financial incentives provided by the State Governments.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] These included tax concessions and access to land at a lower cost, which reduced the cost of clearing and made land development more economically attractive.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Land clearing was also undertaken to raise land values, as cleared land held higher market values compared to uncleared land.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] From 1925 until 1987, the Rural Credits Development Fund aided rural development.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Additional funding for rural expansion also became available through institutions such as the Commonwealth Development Bank, which provided loans that often included land development.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Financial deregulation in the 1970s further increased the availability of loans meant for property development and clearing.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Before to the early 1970s, landholders were able to deduct the full cost of clearing native vegetation.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Then, changes were introduced in 1973, which reduced the concessions by spreading deductions over a longer period.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] By the late 1980s and early 90s, opinions toward land management began to shift, with greater acknowledgement of land degradation and the environmental impacts often associated with extensive clearing.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] This coincided with the removal of many financial incentives and the introduction of stronger regulatory controls.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] As a result, clearing rates declined in many parts of Australia during the 1990s, although clearing continued in some regions.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Land clearing in Australia is influenced by multiple factors, including agricultural expansion, urban and infrastructure development, timber extraction, bushfires and broader economic and policy incentives.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Agricultural expansion, particularly clearing land for livestock grazing and crop production, is a primary driver of land clearing in Australia.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Hundreds of thousands of hectares of native vegetation are removed each year to create pasture for cattle and sheep, and to support crops such as cotton.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] In Queensland, a large proportion of recent clearing, an estimated 86% in 2022-2023, was for the expansion of grazing land.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Large areas of native vegetation have been cleared to create pasture for livestock, especially in Queensland, where the majority of recent clearing has been linked to beef production.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Cropping systems such as wheat production have also contributed to historic clearing in fertile regions, including parts of New South Wales.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Economic research has shown that clearing rates tend to increase during periods of favorable commodity prices, as higher potential revenue encourages landholders to expand agricultural operations.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Urban development contributes to land clearing when native vegetation is removed to make space for housing, infrastructure, and industry related land uses.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] While the majority of urban expansion does occur on previously cleared land, growth in regional and peri-urban areas can also result in new clearing of native forest or woodland.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Urban-related clearing often occurs in areas near major cities and regional centers where residential and commercial land demand intersects with remaining native vegetation, contributing to ongoing reductions in forest and bushland cover.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Logging and the harvesting of native forest products have also contributed to land clearing in Australia.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] In some forest regions, large areas have been cleared for timber production, with remaining vegetation often burned or removed as part of logging operations.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] This type of logging alters forest structure and reduces habitat availability for native species.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Native forest logging has continued, including areas where tall forests are still used for timber and wood products, despite regulatory efforts to reduce the impact.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Bushfires in Australia are frequently occurring events during the hotter months of the year.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Bushfires can result in the loss of vegetation and tree cover across large areas.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] While fire is a natural part of many Australian ecosystems, high-severity fires can cause longer-term reductions in forest and woodland cover.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] In some cases, the vegetation that regrows after fire is later cleared, particularly in grazing areas where regrowth may be removed to maintain pasture.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] This type of secondary clearing can increase overall vegetation loss following major fire events.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Higher agricultural commodity prices, including cattle and crop prices, are associated with increased land clearing, as landowners tend to expand production during periods of strong market conditions.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Analyses of land clearing trends in New South Wales indicate that changes in livestock and crop prices account for a substantial share of variation in clearing rates.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Government management policies have also influenced clearing patterns, with regulatory changes linked to a shift away from first-time clearing and toward re-clearing of previously cleared land.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Land clearing destroys plants and local ecosystems and removes the food and habitat on which other native species rely.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Clearing allows weeds and invasive animals to spread, affects greenhouse gas emissions and can lead to soil degradation, such as erosion and salinity, which in turn can affect water quality.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] The following table shows the native vegetation inventory assessment of native vegetation by type prior to European settlement and as at 2001–2004.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] As the land cover is crucial to land condition, land clearing exerts significant pressure on land condition.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Removal of vegetation also leaves soil bare and vulnerable to erosion.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Soil stability is essential to avoid land degradation.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Soil erosion is very significant pressure on land condition because it undermines existing vegetation and habitats and inhibits vegetation and other biotas that inhabit the vegetation from re-establishing, thus resulting in a "negative" feedback loop.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Terrestrial vegetation is a source of nutrient replenishment for soils.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] If vegetation is removed, there is less biological matter available to break down and replenish the nutrients in the soil.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Exposing soil to erosion leads to further nutrient depletion.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Soil erosion from deforested land has also affected the water quality around the Great Barrier Reef.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Another consequence of land clearing is dryland salinity.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Dryland salinity is the movement of salt to the land surface via groundwater.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] In Australia, there are vast amounts of salt stored beneath the land surface.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Much of Australian native vegetation has adapted to low rainfall conditions, and use deep root systems to take advantage of any available water beneath the surface.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] These help to store salt in the earth, by keeping groundwater levels low enough so that salt is not pushed to the surface.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] However, with land clearing, the reduced amount of water that previously got pumped up by the roots of the trees means that the water table rises towards the surface, dissolving salt in the process.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Salinity reduces plant productivity and affects the health of rivers and streams.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Salinity also affects the lifespan of roads and other infrastructure, affecting the economy and transportation.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Land clearing is a major cause of habitat loss and fragmentation in Australia and is listed as a key threat to many threatened plant and animal species.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] The removal of native vegetation reduces habitat availability and food and shelter resources, increasing the risk of population decline and extinction.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] National conservation assessments indicate that habitat loss linked to deforestation affects a large proportion of threatened species.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Of approximately 1,250 threatened plant species and 390 threatened terrestrial animal species, land clearing and associated habitat degradation are identified as threats for 964 plant species and 286 animal species.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Species affected include Carnaby's cockatoo, the southern cassowary, Bennett's tree-kangaroo, the Cape York rock-wallaby, the black-flanked rock-wallaby, and the koala, which is classified as Vulnerable in Queensland and New South Wales.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Land clearing contributes to climate change by releasing carbon stored in vegetation and soils and by reducing the capacity of ecosystems to absorb carbon dioxide.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] When trees are removed or burned, stored carbon is released into the atmosphere, increasing greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Deforestation and forest degradation account for a significant share of global greenhouse gas emissions, and land clearing remains an important source of emissions within Australia's land-use sector.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Vegetation loss can also influence local and regional climate conditions by reducing shade and moisture and increasing surface temperatures.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] An organisation checked the impacts on climate extremes and droughts by analysing daily rainfall and surface temperature output from the Mark 3 GCM.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] This work, the first of its kind, demonstrated an increase in the number of dry days (<1mm rainfall) and hot days (maximum temperature >35 °C), a decrease in daily rainfall intensity and cumulative rainfall on rain days, and an increase in duration of droughts under modified land-cover conditions.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] These changes were statistically significant for all years across eastern Australia and especially pronounced during strong El Niño events.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] These studies have demonstrated that LCC has exacerbated the mean climate anomaly and climate extremes in the southwest and eastern Australia, thus resulting in longer-lasting and more severe droughts.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Clearing patterns differ across Australia, however Queensland has continued to drive the majority of national vegetation loss.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] In 2022-2023 the state cleared 332,015 hectares for pasture expansion.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Roughly half of those hectares were within Great Barrier Reef catchments, an area where rainfall lands in rivers that flow to the reef.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] These catchments raise concern due to sediment runoff and erosion potentially impacting the reef's water quality.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] The Brigalow Belt and Mulga lands make up the majority of Queensland's hotspot regions, where modeling shows high probabilities for future clearing, as well as significant overlap with threatened vegetation communities.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] In more inland, pastoral zones of New South Wales and South Australia, similar pressures occur, as clearing is often linked to grazing.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] In Tasmania, industrial logging and land clearing continue in areas near protected forests, including parts of the Takayna/Tarkineregion.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Photo documentation shows the removal of eucalypt forests, old-growth stands, and habitat for species such as the glossy black cockatoo.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Urban expansion is also contributing to localized clearing along the eastern seaboard of Australia, specifically in south-east Queensland and peri-urban regions of New South Wales, where the removal of koala feed trees has increased habitat decline.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Indigenous peoples in Australia have manage landscapes, using practices such as frequent, low-intensity cultural burning to maintain open grasslands, woodlands, and diverse plant communities.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Research from northwest Tasmania suggests that many areas historically described as natural grasslands were shaped by long-term Aboriginal fire management.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] When these practices declined following British colonization, vegetation structure changed rapidly, with dense shrub and rainforest species growing into the previously open ecosystems.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] These findings suggest that the condition of some pre-colonial landscapes depended on continued Indigenous land stewardship.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Modern land clearing and mining have also been shown to occur on or near Indigenous lands, affecting clean water, bush foods, and soil stability that Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities rely on.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Reviews of mining impacts show that vegetation loss and habitat disturbance can undermine cultural practices linked to specific species and landscapes.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] National reports on deforestation also note that large-scale clearing for agriculture, forestry, mining, and development can damage areas of cultural significance, including songlines, sacred sites, and Country cared for by First Nations peoples.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] In many cases, clearing occurs without the consent of Aboriginals, contributing to what some describe as degraded Country.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] The combined ecological and cultural effects have led to increased calls for land-clearing policy, conservation planning, and restoration programs to be developed in partnership with First Nations communities, recognizing Indigenous rights.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Land clearing laws have been a political football for decades.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] From the 1970s onwards unions and environmentalists have challenged the clearing of forests, beaches and other specific sites.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Since the 1980s, the rate of land clearing has declined due to changing attitudes and greater awareness of the damaging effects of the clearing.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] The Queensland and New South Wales governments implemented bans on land clearing during the 1990s and early 2000s.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Australia remains a deforestation front, the only developed nation to do so.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Both Queensland and New South Wales monitor land clearing on an annual basis using satellite imagery under the Statewide Landcover and Trees Study.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Clearing is now controlled by legislation in Western Australia, South Australia, Victoria, New South Wales, and to a lesser degree in Queensland.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Land clearing controls differ substantially between jurisdictions, and despite growing awareness of the effect of land degradation, controls on clearing have been generally opposed by farmers.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Depending on the proximity to high risk bush fire zones in each state, the 10/30 rule or the 10/50 rule might apply.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] This allows the clearing of trees within 10 meters of homes or clearing undergrowth within 30 or 50 meters of home.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] This reduces fuel for fire near homes which has proven effective since implementation.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Clearing of native vegetation in NSW is regulated by the *Local Land Services Act 2013* (NSW) and by the protections on the habitat of threatened species contained in the *Biodiversity Conservation Act 2016* (NSW).
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] It is also regulated by development control and Environmental Planning Instruments (EPIs) under land use planning law, namely the *Environmental Planning and Assessment Act 1979* (NSW).
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Federal law in the form of the *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* (Cth) may also apply if there are federally protected threatened species (plant or animal) or endangered ecological communities present on the land in question.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Exempt species are outlined in the *Biosecurity Act 2015* and can be cleared by property owners at any time.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] The Berejiklian government eased vegetation protection laws in 2017.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] According to the state government the state lost 54,000 hectares of woody vegetation in 2019.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Clearing of native vegetation in Queensland is principally regulated by the *Vegetation Management Act 1999* and the *Vegetation Management (Regrowth Clearing Moratorium) Act 2009*.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Clearing rates in Queensland declined from peaks in the 1990s, after a successful campaign from conservation groups and communities throughout Queensland.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] In 2018, the state government passed legislation that banned broadscale clearing of remnant vegetation.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] The reforms aimed to protect high value regrowth.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Clearing of native vegetation in SA is principally regulated by the *Native Vegetation Act 1991* (SA).
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] The Federal *EPBC Act* may also apply (see above).
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] In urban areas or cities, tree removal is governed by local council laws outlined in what's called a Tree Preservation Order (TPO).
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] This set of laws is more specific to reflect the localized objectives for urban forest retention by the council.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Common objectives include creating healthier ecosystems, improving biodiversity and mitigating the heat island effect through tree retention and scheduled tree planting programs.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] TPO's will typically include a significant tree register which lists individual or groups of protected trees and their locations which cannot be removed under any circumstances.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] TPO's also come with exemptions which allow property owners to remove trees without prior approval.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Exemptions may include the maximum height and spread of trees that need council consent for removal and a list of exempt species that can be removed irrespective of height and spread.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Current restoration efforts in Australia focus on re-establishing native vegetation, improving land conditions, and reducing the environmental impacts associated with past clearing.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Conservation organizations have reported that areas affected by extensive clearing often require more long-term rehabilitation, such as erosion control, replanting programs, and measures to stabilize soil and waterways.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Riparian environments, land along riversides, are a noted priority for ongoing restoration projects, as vegetation loss has contributed to declining water quality and increased sedimentation in major river systems.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Current assessments have identified eastern Australia as a global deforestation hotspot, with conservation organizations arguing that there should be stronger protections to limit clearing and support ecosystem recovery.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Proposed strategies include expanding native vegetation safeguards, improving monitoring frameworks, encouraging landholders to retain or restore habitats on their land, and for policymakers to increase laws surrounding land clearing.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Conservation organizations present these approaches as necessary to maintain remaining forest cover and reduce the pressures behind biodiversity decline.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Future restoration outcomes are closely linked to policy and economic conditions.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] Current research indicates that fluctuations in commodity prices influence land-clearing rates, sometimes reducing the effectiveness of regulatory measures.
[src:blockade-novel/logging-in-australia] The outlook for recovery depends on continued investment in rehabilitation programs, improved monitoring, and coordinated approaches between governments, landholders, and conservation organizations.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] A **protagonist** (from Ancient Greek πρωταγωνιστής*(*prōtagōnistḗs*)* 'one who plays the first part, chief actor') is the main character of a story.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] The protagonist makes key decisions that affect the plot, primarily influencing the story and propelling it forward, and is often the character who faces the most significant obstacles and choices.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] If a story contains a subplot, or is a narrative made up of several stories, then each subplot may have its own protagonist.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] The protagonist is the character whose fate is most closely followed by the reader or audience, and who is opposed by the antagonist.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] The antagonist provides obstacles and complications and creates conflicts that test the protagonist, revealing the strengths and weaknesses of the protagonist's character, and having the protagonist develop as a result.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] A particularly noble, virtuous, or accomplished protagonist is commonly called a *hero,* though the terms are not synonyms.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] The earliest known example of a protagonist can be found in the Epic of Gilgamesh, dated around the 3rd millennium BCE.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] However, the term originated only later with the dramatic performances of Ancient Greece.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] At first these involved merely dancing and recitation by the chorus, but then, according to Aristotle's *Poetics*, a poet named Thespis introduced the idea of one actor stepping out and engaging in a dialogue with the chorus.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] This was the invention of tragedy, and occurred about 536 B.C.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Then the poet Aeschylus, in his plays, introduced a second actor, inventing the idea of dialogue between two characters.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Sophocles then wrote plays that included a third actor.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] A description of the protagonist's origin cited that during the early period of Greek drama, the protagonist served as the author, the director, and the actor and that these roles were only separated and allocated to different individuals later.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] There is also a claim that the poet did not assign or create the protagonist as well as other terms for actors such as *deuteragonist* and *tritagonist* primarily because he only gave actors their appropriate part.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] However, these actors were assigned their specific areas at the stage with the protagonist always entering from the middle door or that the dwelling of the deuteragonist (second most important character) should be on the right hand, and the tritagonist (third most important character), the left.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] In Ancient Greece, the protagonist is distinguished from the term "hero", which was used to refer to a human who became a semi-divine being in the narrative.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] In literary terms, a hero (masculine) or heroine (feminine) protagonist is typically admired for their achievements and noble qualities.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Heroes are lauded for their strength, courage, virtuousness, and honor, and are considered to be the "good guys" of the narrative.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Examples include DC Comics' Superman (hero) and Katniss Everdeen from *The Hunger Games* (heroine).
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] An antihero (sometimes spelled as anti-hero) or antiheroine is a main character in a story who lacks conventional heroic qualities and attributes such as idealism, courage, and morality.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Examples include Holden Caulfield from *The Catcher in the Rye*, Scarlett O'Hara from *Gone With the Wind*, and Jay Gatsby from *The Great Gatsby*.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] A tragic hero is the protagonist of a tragedy.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Examples include Oedipus from *Oedipus Rex* and Prince Hamlet from Shakespeare's *Hamlet*.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] In narratives that feature multiple protagonists, such as ensemble casts or multi-perspective storytelling, one character is often identified as the main protagonist.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] This character typically receives the greatest narrative focus and plays the most significant role in advancing the central plot, even though other protagonists may have substantial and independent story arcs.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] The terms protagonist and main protagonist are frequently used interchangeably, particularly in works centered on a single character.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] However, the distinction becomes more relevant in stories with multiple protagonists, where the main protagonist serves as the primary organizing figure of the narrative.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] The main protagonist is not necessarily the most morally virtuous character, nor must they function as a traditional hero.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Rather, their defining characteristic is narrative centrality.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] In some works, the prominence of the main protagonist may shift over time or be shared, reflecting evolving storytelling conventions that challenge rigid protagonist–antagonist structures.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] The protagonist is not always conventionally good.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Contrasting the hero protagonist, a villain protagonist is a protagonist who is a villain, driving the story forward regardless of the evil qualities the main character has.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] These traits can include being cruel, malicious, and wicked.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Examples include Humbert Humbert in Vladimir Nabokov's *Lolita*, Richard III in the eponymous play by William Shakespeare, Frank Underwood in *House of Cards*, Tony Soprano from *The Sopranos*, Light Yagami in the *Death Note* franchise, and Walter White from *Breaking Bad*.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] When a supporting protagonist appears, the story is told from the perspective of a character who appears to be minor.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] This character may be more peripheral from the events of the story and are not as involved within the "main action" of the plot.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] The supporting protagonist may be telling the story while viewing another character as the main influence of the plot.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] One example is Nick in *The Great Gatsby*.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Euripides' play *Hippolytus* may be considered to have two protagonists, though one at a time.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Phaedra is the protagonist of the first half, who dies partway through the play.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Her stepson, the titular Hippolytus, assumes the dominant role in the second half of the play.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] In Henrik Ibsen's play *The Master Builder*, the protagonist is the architect Halvard Solness.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] The young woman, Hilda Wangel, whose actions lead to the death of Solness, is the antagonist.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] In Shakespeare's play *Romeo and Juliet*, Romeo is the protagonist.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] He is actively in pursuit of his relationship with Juliet, and the audience is invested in that story.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Tybalt, as an antagonist, opposes Romeo and attempts to thwart the relationship.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] In Shakespeare's play *Hamlet*, Prince Hamlet, who seeks revenge for the murder of his father, is the protagonist.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] The antagonist is the character who most opposes Hamlet, Claudius (though, in many ways, Hamlet is his own antagonist).
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Sometimes, a work will have a false protagonist, who may seem to be the protagonist, but then may disappear unexpectedly.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] The character Marion in Alfred Hitchcock's film *Psycho* (1960) is an example.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] A novel may contain a number of narratives, each with its own protagonist.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Alexander Solzhenitsyn's *The First Circle*, for example, depicts a variety of characters imprisoned and living in a gulag camp.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Leo Tolstoy's *War and Peace* depicts fifteen major characters involved in or affected by a war.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] Though many people equate protagonists with the term hero and possessing heroic qualities, it is not necessary, as even villainous characters can be protagonists.
[src:blockade-novel/protagonist] In some cases, the protagonist is not a human: in Richard Adams' novel *Watership Down,* a group of anthropomorphised rabbits, led by the protagonist Hazel, escape their warren after seeing a vision of its destruction, starting a perilous journey to find a new home.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The state encompasses a range of climates and geographical features from its temperate coastal and central regions to the Victorian Alps in the northeast and the semi-arid northwest.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The state is also home to four of Australia's 20 largest cities: Melbourne, Geelong, Ballarat and Bendigo.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria is home to numerous Aboriginal groups, including the Boonwurrung, the Brataualung, the Djadjawurrung, the Gunai, the Gunditjmara, the Taungurung, the Wathaurong, the Wurundjeri, and the Yorta Yorta.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] There were more than 30 Aboriginal languages spoken in the area prior to European colonisation.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In 1770 James Cook claimed the east coast of the Australian continent for the Kingdom of Great Britain.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The first European settlement in the area occurred in 1803 at Sullivan Bay.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Much of Victoria was included in 1836 in the Port Phillip District of New South Wales.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Named in honour of Queen Victoria, Victoria was separated from New South Wales and established as a separate Crown colony in 1851, achieving responsible government in 1855.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Victorian gold rush in the 1850s and 1860s significantly increased Victoria's population and wealth.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] By the time of Australian Federation in 1901, Melbourne had become the largest city in Australasia, and was the seat of Federal government until Canberra became the national capital in 1927.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The state continued to grow strongly through various periods of the 20th and 21st centuries due to high levels of international and interstate migration.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Melbourne hosts a number of museums, art galleries, and theatres; in 2016 a sports marketing company named it the world's sporting capital.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria has 38 seats in the Australian House of Representatives and 12 seats in the Australian Senate.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] At state level, the Parliament of Victoria consists of the Legislative Assembly and the Legislative Council.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Labor Party, led by Jacinta Allan as premier, has governed Victoria since 2014.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Governor of Victoria, the representative of the monarch in the state, is currently Margaret Gardner.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria is divided into 79 local government areas, as well as several unincorporated areas which the state administers directly.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The state of Victoria was home to many Aboriginal Australian nations that had occupied the land for tens of thousands of years before European settlement.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] According to Gary Presland, Aboriginal people have lived in Victoria for about 40,000 years,<ref﻿*Presland, Gary (1997).
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] *The First Residents of Melbourne's Western Region* (Revised ed.).
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] There is some evidence to show that people were living in the Maribyrnong River valley, near present day Keilor, about 40,000 years ago*</ref> living a semi-nomadic existence of fishing, hunting and gathering, and farming eels.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] At the Keilor Archaeological Site, a human hearth excavated in 1971 was radiocarbon-dated to about 31,000 years BP, making Keilor one of the earliest sites of human habitation in Australia.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] A cranium found at the site has been dated at between 12,000 and 14,700 years BP.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] During the Ice Age about 20,000 years BP, the area that is now Port Phillip bay was dry land, and the Yarra and Werribee rivers met, flowed through the heads, then across the plain that is now Bass Strait to the ocean near Tasmania.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Tasmania and the Bass Strait islands separated from mainland Australia around 12,000 BP, when the sea level was approximately 50m below present levels.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Port Phillip was flooded by post-glacial sea level rise between 8,000 and 6,000 years ago.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Oral history and creation stories from the Wada wurrung, Woiwurrung and Bun wurrung languages describe the flooding of the bay.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Hobsons Bay was once a kangaroo hunting ground.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Creation stories describe how Bunjil was responsible for the formation of the bay, or the bay was flooded when the Yarra River was created.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria, like Queensland, was named after Queen Victoria, who had been on the British throne for 14 years when the colony was established in 1851.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] After the founding of the colony of New South Wales in 1788, Australia was divided into an eastern half named New South Wales and a western half named New Holland, under the administration of the colonial government in Sydney.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The first British settlement in the area later known as Victoria was established in October 1803 under Lieutenant-Governor David Collins at Sullivan Bay on Port Phillip.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] It consisted of 402 people (five government officials, nine officers of marines, two drummers, and 39 privates, five soldiers' wives and a child, 307 convicts, 17 convicts' wives, and seven children).
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] They had been sent from England in HMS *Calcutta* under the command of Captain Daniel Woodriff, principally out of fear that the French, who had been exploring the area, might establish their own settlement and thereby challenge British rights to the continent.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In 1826, Colonel Stewart, Captain Samuel Wright, and Lieutenant Burchell were sent in HMS *Fly* (Captain Wetherall) and the brigs *Dragon* and *Amity*, took a number of convicts and a small force composed of detachments of the 3rd and 93rd regiments.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The expedition established its headquarters at Settlement Point, on the eastern side of the bay near present-day Corinella).
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] This site served as the base of the outpost until Western Port was abandoned approximately 12 months later, as ordered by Governor Ralph Darling.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria's next settlement was at Portland, on the south west coast of what is now Victoria.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Edward Henty settled Portland Bay in 1834.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Melbourne was founded in 1835 by John Batman, who set up a base in Indented Head, and John Pascoe Fawkner.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] From settlement, the region around Melbourne was known as the Port Phillip District, a separately administered part of New South Wales.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Shortly after, the site now known as Geelong was surveyed by Assistant Surveyor W.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] And in 1838, Geelong was officially declared a town, despite earlier European settlements dating back to 1826.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] On 6 June 1835, just under two years before Melbourne was officially recognised as a settlement, John Batman, the leader of the Port Phillip Association presented Wurundjeri Elders with a land use agreement.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] This document, now referred to as the Batman treaty, was later given to the British government to claim that local Aboriginal people had given Batman access to their land in exchange for goods and rations.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The treaty itself was declared void as Batman did not have permission from the Crown to establish Melbourne.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Today, the meaning and interpretation of this treaty is contested.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Some argue it was a pretence for taking Aboriginal land in exchange for trinkets, while others argue it was significant in that it sought to recognise Aboriginal land rights.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The exact location of the meeting between Batman and the Kulin men with whom he made the treaty is unknown, although it is believed to have been by the Merri Creek.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] According to historian Meyer Eidelson, it is generally believed to have occurred on the Merri near modern-day Rushall Station.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] On 1 July 1851, writs were issued for the election of the first Victorian Legislative Council, and the absolute independence of Victoria from New South Wales was established proclaiming a new Colony of Victoria.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Days later, still in 1851 gold was discovered near Ballarat, and subsequently at Bendigo.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Later discoveries occurred at many sites across Victoria.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] This triggered one of the largest gold rushes the world has ever seen.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The colony grew rapidly in both population and economic power.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In 10 years, the population of Victoria increased sevenfold from 76,000 to 540,000.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] All sorts of gold records were produced, including the "richest shallow alluvial goldfield in the world" and the largest gold nugget.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In the decade 1851–1860 Victoria produced 20 million ounces of gold, one-third of the world's output.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In 1855 the Geological Survey collected and determined the major ion chemistry for groundwater in Victoria.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Immigrants arrived from all over the world to search for gold, especially from Ireland and China.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] By 1857, 26,000 Chinese miners worked in Victoria, and their legacy is particularly strong in Bendigo and its environs.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In 1854 at Ballarat, an armed rebellion against the government of Victoria was made by miners protesting against mining taxes (the "Eureka Stockade").
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Although British military forces suppressed the uprising, the armed confrontation compelled colonial authorities to reform the administration of mining concessions—significantly reducing burdensome licence fees—and expand the electoral franchise.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The following year, the Imperial Parliament granted Victoria responsible government with the passage of the Colony of Victoria Act 1855.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Some of the leaders of the Eureka rebellion went on to become members of the Victorian Parliament.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In 1857, reflecting the growing presence of Irish Catholic immigrants, John O'Shanassy became the colony's second Premier with the former Young Irelander, Charles Gavan Duffy as his deputy.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Melbourne's Protestant establishment was ill-prepared "to countenance so startling a novelty".
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In 1858–59, *Melbourne Punch* cartoons linked Duffy and O'Shanassy to the terrors of the French Revolution.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In 1862 Duffy's Land Act attempted, but failed, through a system of extended pastoral licences, to break the land-holding monopoly of the so-called "squatter" class.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In 1871, having led, on behalf of small farmers, opposition to Premier Sir James McCulloch's land tax, Duffy, himself, was briefly Premier.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In 1893 widespread bank failures brought to an end a sustained period of prosperity and of increasingly wild speculation in land and construction.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Melbourne nonetheless retained, as the legacy of the gold rush, its status as Australia's primary financial centre and largest city.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In 1901, Victoria became a state in the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] While Canberra was being built, Melbourne served until 1927 as the country's first federal capital.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria's northern border follows a straight line (the Black–Allan Line) from Cape Howe to the start of the Murray River and then follows the Murray River as the remainder of the northern border.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] On the Murray River, the border is the southern bank of the river.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] This precise definition was not established until 1980, when a ruling by Justice Ninian Stephen of the High Court of Australia settled the question as to which state had jurisdiction in the unlawful death of a man on an island in the middle of the river.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The ruling clarified that no part of the watercourse is in Victoria.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The border also rests at the southern end of the Great Dividing Range, which stretches along the east coast and terminates west of Ballarat.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] It is bordered by South Australia to the west and shares Australia's shortest land border with Tasmania.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The official border between Victoria and Tasmania is at 39°12' S, which passes through Boundary Islet in the Bass Strait for 85 metres.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] There are extensive semi-arid plains to the west and northwest.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] There is an extensive series of river systems in Victoria.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Most notable is the Murray River system.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The state symbols include the pink heath (state flower), Leadbeater's possum (state animal) and the helmeted honeyeater (state bird).
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Ecological communities include Victorian Volcanic Plain grasslands, Northern Plains Grassland and Gippsland Plains Grassy Woodland, all of which are critically endangered.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] According to Geoscience Australia, the geographic centre of Victoria is located in Mandurang at 36° 51' 15"S, 144° 16' 52" E.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The small rural locality is located 10 km (6 mi) south of Bendigo.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Due to its central location and the region's historical ties to the gold rush, the town is widely regarded as the "Heart of Gold".
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The state's capital, Melbourne, contains about 70% of the state's population and dominates its economy, media, and culture.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] For other cities and towns, see list of localities (Victoria) and local government areas of Victoria.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria is divided into distinct geographic regions, most commonly for the purposes of economic development, while others for land management (agriculture or conservation) and for censusing (statistical or meteorological) or electoral purposes.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The most commonly used regions are those created by the state government for the purposes of economic development.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In addition to Greater Melbourne, the Victoria State Government has divided Victoria into five regions covering all parts of the state.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Australian Bureau of Meteorology defines regions for its own purposes, some of which share names with the economic regions, even though the exact boundaries may not correlate.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] This is a list of places in the Australian state of Victoria by population.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Urban centres are defined by the Australian Bureau of Statistics as being a population cluster of 1,000 or more people.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria has a varied climate that ranges from semi-arid temperate with hot summers in the north-west, to temperate and cool along the coast.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria's main land feature, the Great Dividing Range, produces a cooler, mountain climate in the centre of the state.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Winters along the coast of the state, particularly around Melbourne, are relatively mild (*see chart*).
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The coastal plain south of the Great Dividing Range has Victoria's mildest climate.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Air from the Southern Ocean helps reduce the heat of summer and the cold of winter.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Melbourne and other large cities are located in this temperate region.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Mallee and upper Wimmera are Victoria's warmest regions with hot winds blowing from nearby semi-deserts.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Average temperatures exceed 32 °C (90 °F) during summer and 15 °C (59 °F) in winter.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Except at cool mountain elevations, the inland monthly temperatures are 2–7 °C (4–13 °F) warmer than around Melbourne (see chart).
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria's highest maximum temperature of 48.9 °C (120.0 °F) was recorded in Walepup/ Hopetoun on 27 January 2026, during the January 2026 heatwave affecting the State.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Victorian Alps in the northeast are the coldest part of Victoria.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Alps are part of the Great Dividing Range mountain system extending east–west through the centre of Victoria.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Mean maximum temperatures are less than 9 °C (48 °F) in winter and below 0 °C (32 °F) in the highest parts of the ranges.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The state's lowest minimum temperature of −11.7 °C (10.9 °F) was recorded at Omeo on 15 June 1965, and again at Falls Creek on 3 July 1970.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Rainfall in Victoria increases from south to the northeast, with higher averages in areas of high altitude.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Mean annual rainfall exceeds 1,800 millimetres (71 inches) in some parts of the northeast but is less than 280 mm (11 in) in the Mallee.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Rain is heaviest in the Otway Ranges and Gippsland in southern Victoria and in the mountainous northeast.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Snow generally falls only in the mountains and hills in the centre of the state.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Rain falls most frequently in winter, but summer precipitation is heavier.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Rainfall is most reliable in Gippsland and the Western District, making them both leading farming areas.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria's highest recorded daily rainfall was 377.8 mm (14.87 in) at Tidal River in Wilsons Promontory National Park on 23 March 2011.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] It is estimated that on 30 June 2025, Victoria had a population of 7,074,468.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Australian Bureau of Statistics estimates that the population may well reach 10.3 million by 2051.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria's founding Anglo-Celtic population has been supplemented by successive waves of migrants from Southern and Eastern Europe, Asia and, most recently, Africa and the Middle East.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria's population is ageing in proportion with the average of the remainder of the Australian population.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] About 72% of Victorians are Australian-born.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] This figure falls to around 66% in Melbourne but rises to higher than 95% in some rural areas in the north west of the state.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Less than 1% of Victorians identify themselves as Aboriginal.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] More than 75% of Victorians live in Melbourne, located in the state's south.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The greater Melbourne metropolitan area is home to an estimated 5,207,145 people.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Urban centres outside Melbourne include Geelong, Ballarat, Bendigo, Shepparton, Mildura, Warrnambool, Wodonga and the Latrobe Valley.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria is Australia's most urbanised state: nearly 90% of residents living in cities and towns.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] State Government efforts to decentralise population have included an official campaign run since 2003 to encourage Victorians to settle in regional areas, however Melbourne continues to rapidly outpace these areas in terms of population growth.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] 0.8% of the population, or 47,788 people, identified as Indigenous Australians (Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders) in 2016.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] At the 2016 census, 64.9% of residents were born in Australia.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The other most common countries of birth were England (2.9%), India (2.9%), mainland China (2.7%), New Zealand (1.6%) and Vietnam (1.4%).
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] As of the 2016 census, 72.2% of Victorians speak English at home.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In the 2016 Census, 47.9% of Victorians described themselves as Christian, 10.6% stated that they followed other religions and 32.1% stated that they had no religion or held secular or other spiritual beliefs.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In the survey, 31.7% of Victorians stated they had no religion, Roman Catholics were 23.2%, 9.4% did not answer the question, 9% were Anglican and 3.5% were Eastern Orthodox.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In 2017 the proportion of couples marrying in a civil ceremony in Victoria was 77.3%; the other 22.7% were married in a religious ceremony.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The government predicts that nearly a quarter of Victorians will be aged over 60 by 2021.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The 2016 census revealed that Australian median age has crept upward from 35 to 37 since 2001, which reflects the population growth peak of 1969–72.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In 2017, Victoria recorded a TFR of 1.724.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In the year ending September 2020, the statistics were skewed by the introduction of six new public safety offences relating to the COVID-19 pandemic in Australia.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Total offences numbered 551,710, with 32,713 of these being breaches of Chief Health Officer Directions.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The total offences occurred at a rate of 8,227 per 100,000 people, up 4.4% on the previous year.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] While there have been some dips along the way, the rate of recorded offences have increased year on year since 2011, when the figure was 6,937.7 offences per 100,000 people.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria has a parliamentary form of government based on the Westminster System.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Legislative power resides in the Parliament consisting of the Governor (the representative of the King), the executive (the Government), and two legislative chambers.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Parliament of Victoria consists of the lower house Legislative Assembly, the upper house Legislative Council and the monarch.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Eighty-eight members of the Legislative Assembly are elected to four-year terms from single-member electorates.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In November 2006, the Victorian Legislative Council elections were held under a new multi-member proportional representation system.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The State of Victoria was divided into eight electorates with each electorate represented by five representatives elected by Single Transferable Vote.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The total number of upper house members was reduced from 44 to 40 and their term of office is now the same as the lower house members—four years.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Elections for the Victorian Parliament are now fixed and occur in November every four years.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Prior to the 2006 election, the Legislative Council consisted of 44 members elected to eight-year terms from 22 two-member electorates.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Premier of Victoria is the leader of the political party or coalition with the most seats in the Legislative Assembly.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Premier is the public face of government and, with cabinet, sets the legislative and political agenda.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Cabinet consists of representatives elected to either house of parliament.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] It is responsible for managing areas of government that are not exclusively vested in the Commonwealth, by the Australian Constitution, such as education, health and law enforcement.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The current Premier of Victoria is Jacinta Allan.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Executive authority is vested in the Governor of Victoria who represents and is appointed by the monarch.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The post is usually filled by a retired prominent Victorian.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The governor acts on the advice of the premier and cabinet.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The current Governor of Victoria is Margaret Gardner.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria has a written constitution enacted in 1975, but based on the 1855 colonial constitution, passed by the United Kingdom Parliament as the Victoria Constitution Act 1855, which establishes the Parliament as the state's law-making body for matters coming under state responsibility.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Victorian Constitution can be amended by the Parliament of Victoria, except for certain "entrenched" provisions that require either an absolute majority in both houses, a three-fifths majority in both houses, or the approval of the Victorian people in a referendum, depending on the provision.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] To this day, not a single referendum has been held to change the Victorian Constitution.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria is considered by some analysts to be the most progressive state in the nation.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The state recorded the highest *Yes* votes of any state in the republic referendum, same-sex marriage survey and Indigenous Voice referendum.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victorians are said to be "generally socially progressive, supportive of multiculturalism, wary of extremes of any kind".
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Premier Jacinta Allan leads the Victorian Labor Party who replaced Daniel Andrews after his resignation in September 2023.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Labor has been in power since the November 2014 Victorian state election, and has been in power in 31 of the 42 years since 1982.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The centre-left Australian Labor Party (ALP), the centre-right Liberal Party of Australia, the rural-based National Party of Australia, and the left-wing environmentalist Australian Greens are Victoria's main political parties.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Traditionally, Labor is strongest in Melbourne's working and middle class western, northern and inner-city suburbs, and the regional cities of Ballarat, Bendigo and Geelong.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Liberals' main support lies in Melbourne's more affluent eastern suburbs and outer suburbs, and some rural and regional centres.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Nationals are strongest in Victoria's North Western and Eastern rural regional areas.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The Greens, who won their first lower house seats in 2014, are strongest in inner Melbourne.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victorian voters elect 50 representatives to the Parliament of Australia, including 38 members of the House of Representatives and 12 members of the Senate.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Since 1 April 2023, the ALP hold 25 Victorian house seats, the Liberals 10, the Nationals three, the Greens one, and independents the remaining three.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The ALP and the Liberals hold four senate seats each, while the Nationals, Greens, UAP and an independent hold one seat each.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria is incorporated into 79 municipalities for the purposes of local government, including 39 shires, 32 cities, seven rural cities and one borough.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Shire and city councils are responsible for functions delegated by the Victorian parliament, such as city planning, road infrastructure and waste management.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Council revenue comes mostly from property taxes and government grants.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria's state school system dates back to 1872, when the colonial government legislated to make schooling free, secular and compulsory.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The state's public secondary school system began in 1905.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Before then, only private secondary schooling was available.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Today, a Victorian school education consists of seven years of primary schooling (including one preparatory year) and six years of secondary schooling.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The final years of secondary school are optional for children aged over 17.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victorian children generally begin school at age five or six.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] On completing secondary school, students earn the Victorian Certificate of Education (VCE) or Victorian Certificate of Education - Vocational Major (VCE-VM).
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Students who successfully complete their VCE (not including VCE-VM students) also receive an ATAR, to determine university admittance (unless the student is 'going unscored'.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victorian schools are either publicly or privately funded.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Public schools, also known as state or government schools, are funded and run directly by the Victorian Department of Education.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Students do not pay tuition fees, but some extra costs are levied.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Private fee-paying schools include parish schools run by the Roman Catholic Church and independent schools similar to British public schools.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Independent schools are usually affiliated with Protestant churches.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria also has several private Jewish and Islamic primary and secondary schools.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Private schools also receive some public funding.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] All schools must comply with government-set curriculum standards.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In addition, Victoria has six government selective schools, Melbourne High School for boys, MacRobertson Girls' High School for girls, the coeducational schools John Monash Science School, Nossal High School and Suzanne Cory High School, and the Victorian College of the Arts Secondary School.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Students at these schools are exclusively admitted on the basis of an academic selective entry test.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria also offers an online schooling system, called Virtual School Victoria, or VSV.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] As of February 2019, Victoria had 1,529 public schools, 496 Catholic schools and 219 independent schools.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Just under 631,500 students were enrolled in public schools, and just over 357,000 in private schools.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Over 58 per cent of private students attend Catholic schools.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] More than 552,300 students were enrolled in primary schools and more than 418,600 in secondary schools.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Retention rates for the final two years of secondary school were 84.3 per cent for public school students and 91.5 per cent for private school students.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria has about 46,523 full-time teachers.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The first to offer degrees, the University of Melbourne, enrolled its first student in 1855.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The largest, Monash University, has an enrolment of over 83,000 students—more than any other Australian university.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The number of students enrolled in Victorian universities was 418,447 in 2018, an increase of 5.3% on the previous year.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] International students made up 40% of enrolments and account for the highest percentage of pre-paid university tuition fees.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The largest number of enrolments were recorded in the fields of business, administration and economics, with nearly 30% of all students, followed by arts, humanities, and social science, with 18% of enrolments.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Victoria has 12 government-run institutions of technical and further education (TAFE).
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The first vocational institution in the state was the Melbourne Mechanics' Institute (established in 1839), which is now the Melbourne Athenaeum.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] More than 1,000 adult education organisations are registered to provide recognised TAFE programs.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] In 2014, there were 443,000 students enrolled in vocational education in the state.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] By 2018, the number of students in the sector had dropped by 40 per cent to 265,000—a five-year low which the education department attributed to withdrawal of funding to low-quality providers and a societal shift to university education.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The State Library Victoria is the State's research and reference library.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] It is responsible for collecting and preserving Victoria's documentary heritage and making it available through a range of services and programs.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] Material in the collection includes books, newspapers, magazines, journals, manuscripts, maps, pictures, objects, sound and video recordings and databases.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p01] The state has public libraries in most LGAs (typically with multiple branches in their respective municipal areas) and academic libraries in universities, and some special libraries.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The state of Victoria is the second largest economy in Australia after New South Wales, accounting for a quarter of the nation's gross domestic product.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The total gross state product (GSP) at current prices for Victoria was A$459 billion in June 2020, with a GSP per capita of A$68,996.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria is Australia's second-largest agricultural producer in gross value of production, representing about 25 percent of Australia's total food production.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] There are 67,600 people employed in the agricultural industry, making it the 6th largest employer in the state.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] There are about 21,600 farms in the state, managing more than 11.4 million hectares or 50% of the state's total landmass, of which 40% was used for cropping and 50% for grazing.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victorian farms produce nearly 90% of Australian pears and a third of apples.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The main vegetable crops include asparagus, broccoli, carrots, potatoes, and tomatoes.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] More than 14 million sheep and 5 million lambs graze over 10% of Victorian farms, mostly in the state's north and west.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] *Pgt* standard race 126 was the most common Stem Rust (*Puccinia graminis* f. sp.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] *tritici*) race here from 1929 to 1941, as it was for the whole of Australia.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] First detected on Tasmania in 1954, standard race 21 was the most common race by the next year in this state, the southern part of NSW, and Tasmania.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Leaf Rust (*P. triticina*) is known to have been present here, and throughout the continent, at least since European colonization.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] *P. triticina* pathotype 104-2,3,(6),(7),11 was first found here in 1984 and has contributed to populations ever since.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] It is considered to be foreign to Australia due to a difference in pathogenicity and due to its unique *Pgm2 c* allele.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] It is also a leader in stone fruit (*Prunus*) production.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The main vegetable crops include asparagus, broccoli, carrots, potatoes and tomatoes.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Last year, 121,200 metric tons (133,600 short tons) of pears and 270,000 metric tons (300,000 short tons) of tomatoes were produced.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] In 2004, nearly 10 million lambs and sheep were slaughtered for local consumption and export.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria also exports live sheep to the Middle East for meat and to the rest of the world for breeding.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] More than 108,000 metric tons (119,000 short tons) of wool clip was also produced—one-fifth of the Australian total.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria is the centre of dairy farming in Australia.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] It is home to 60% of Australia's 3 million dairy cattle and produces nearly two-thirds of the nation's milk, almost 6.4 billion litres (1.7 billion US gallons).
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The state also has 2.4 million beef cattle, with more than 2.2 million cattle and calves slaughtered each year.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] In 2003–04, Victorian commercial fishing crews and aquaculture industry produced 11,634 metric tons (12,824 short tons) of seafood valued at nearly A$109 million.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Blacklipped abalone is the mainstay of the catch, bringing in A$46 million, followed by southern rock lobster worth A$13.7 million.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Most abalone and rock lobster is exported to Asia.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Most of Australia – including this state – imposed a moratorium on GM canola in 2003 to consider the positives and negatives.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] After consideration the ban here was lifted in 2008 and the state's produced a review of the effects of the moratorium and the expected economic and other effects of adoption or failure to adopt GM canola.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The government finds a benefit of AUS$45 per hectare ($18/acre)/season over conventional.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Late in 2019, the COVID-19 pandemic began, and Australian agriculture was heavily impacted by the resulting supply chain issues.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The scarcity of freight space and disruption to Chinese New Year purchases was particularly painful, with China being Australia's largest export market and a particularly large buyer of live seafood.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] As of 2022 there are almost 100 strawberry farms here, most close to Melbourne CBD in the Yarra Valley.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] They are represented by the Victorian Strawberries organisation, who recommend varieties for production.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria has a diverse range of manufacturing enterprises and Melbourne is considered Australia's most important industrial city.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The post-World War II manufacturing boom was fuelled by international investment, attracted to the state by the availability of cheap land close to the city and inexpensive energy from the Latrobe Valley.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria produced 26.4% of total manufacturing output in Australia in 2015–16, behind New South Wales at 32.4%.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Machinery and equipment manufacturing is the state's most valuable manufacturing activity, followed by food and beverage products, petrochemicals and chemicals.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria also plays an important role in providing goods for the defence industry.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria proportionally relies on manufacturing more than any other state in Australia, constituting 8.6% of total state product; slightly higher than South Australia at 8.0%.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] However, this proportion has been declining for three decades; in 1990 at the time of the early 1990s recession manufacturing constituted 20.3% of total state output.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Manufacturing output peaked in absolute terms in 2008, reaching $28.8 billion and has slowly fallen over the decade to $26.8 billion in 2016 (−0.77% per annum).
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Since 1990, manufacturing employment has also fallen in both aggregate (367,700 to 274,400 workers) and proportional (17.8% to 9.0%) terms.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The strong Australian dollar as a result of the 2000s mining boom, small population and isolation, high wage base and the general shift of manufacturing production towards developing countries have been cited as some of the reasons for this decline.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Historically, Victoria has been a hub for the manufacturing plants of the major car brands Ford, Toyota and Holden; however, closure announcements by all three companies in the 2010s has meant Australia will completely lose their car manufacturing industry by the end of 2017.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Holden's announcement occurred in May 2013 following Ford's decision in December the previous year (Ford's Victorian plants, in Broadmeadows and Geelong, closed in October 2016).
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Toyota followed suit in February 2014 with an expected announcement as without Holden or Ford, local supply chains would struggle to create the economics of scale required to supply one manufacturer.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria adopted the Torrens system of land registration with the *Real Property Act 1862*.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The Torrens system did not replace the common law system but applied only to new land grants and to land that has been voluntarily registered under the Act, and its successors.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The common law system continues to apply to all other private landholdings.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Crown land held in Victoria is managed under the *Crown Land (Reserves) Act 1978* and the *Land Act 1958*.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Mining in Victoria contributes around A$6 billion to the gross state product (~2%) but employs less than 1% of workers.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The Victorian mining industry is concentrated on energy producing minerals, with brown coal, petroleum and gas accounting for nearly 90% of local production.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The oil and gas industries are centred off the coast of Gippsland in the state's east, while brown coal mining and power generation is based in the Latrobe Valley.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] In 1985, oil production from the offshore Gippsland Basin peaked to an annual average of 450,000 barrels (72,000 m3) per day.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] In 2005–2006, the average daily oil production has declined to 83,000 bbl (13,200 m3)/d, but despite the decline Victoria still produces almost 19.5% of crude oil in Australia.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] In the 2005–06 fiscal year, the average gas production was over 700 million cubic feet (20,000,000 m3) per day (M cuft/d) and represented 18% of the total national gas sales, with demand growing at 2% per year.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Campaigning resulted in a prohibition on onshore gas exploration and production in Victoria in 2014,.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] This was partially lifted in 2021 but the state retains a constitutional ban on fracking.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Brown coal is Victoria's leading mineral, with 66 million tonnes mined each year for electricity generation in the Latrobe Valley, Gippsland.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The region is home to the world's largest known reserves of brown coal.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Despite being the historic centre of Australia's gold rush, Victoria today contributes a mere 1% of national gold production.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria also produces limited amounts of gypsum and kaolin.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria's gold production is mostly derived from the Fosterville and Stawell Gold Minees.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Tourism is a significant industry in the state of Victoria, Australia.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The country's second most-populous city, Melbourne was visited by 2.7 million international overnight visitors and 13.5 million domestic overnight visitors during the year ending December 2025.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Named the world's most liveable city from 2011 to 2017 and again in 2026, Melbourne's culture and lifestyle have been increasingly promoted internationally, leading to year-on-year growth of international visitors by 4.4% in 2025.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Other popular tourism activities are gliding, hang-gliding, hot air ballooning and scuba diving.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Major events that explore cultural diversity, music and sports play a big part in Victoria's tourism.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria has the highest population density in any state in Australia, with population centres spread out over most of the state; only the far northwest and the Victorian Alps lack permanent settlement.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] As of October 2013, smoking tobacco is prohibited in the sheltered areas of train stations, and tram and bus stops, as is the use of e-cigarettes.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Between 2012 and 2013, 2002 people were issued with infringement notices.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The state government announced a plan in October 2013 to prohibit smoking on all Victorian railway station platforms and raised tram stops.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The Victorian road network services the population centres, with highways generally radiating from Melbourne and other major cities and rural centres with secondary roads interconnecting the highways to each other.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Many of the highways are built to freeway standard ("M" freeways), while most are generally sealed and of reasonable quality.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Rail transport in Victoria is provided by several private and public railway operators who operate over government-owned lines.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] There are also several smaller freight operators and numerous tourist railways operating over lines which were once parts of a state-owned system.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victorian lines mainly use the 1,600 mm (5 ft 3 in) broad gauge.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] However, the interstate trunk routes, as well as a number of freight lines in the north and west of the state have been converted to 1,435 mm (4 ft 8+1⁄2 in) standard gauge.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Two tourist railways operate over 760 mm (2 ft 6 in) narrow gauge lines, which are the remnants of five formerly government-owned lines which were built in mountainous areas.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Melbourne has the world's largest tram network, currently operated by Yarra Trams.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] As well as being a popular form of public transport, over the last few decades trams have become one of Melbourne's major tourist attractions.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] There are also tourist trams operating over portions of the former Ballarat and Bendigo systems.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] There are also tramway museums at Bylands, Haddon and Hawthorn.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Melbourne Airport is the major domestic and international gateway for the state.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Avalon Airport is the state's second busiest airport, which complements Essendon and Moorabbin Airports to see the remainder of Melbourne's air traffic.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Hamilton Airport, Mildura Airport, Mount Hotham and Portland Airport are the remaining airports with scheduled domestic flights.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] There are no fewer than 27 other airports in the state with no scheduled flights.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The Port of Melbourne is the largest port for containerised and general cargo in Australia, and is located in Melbourne on the mouth of the Yarra River, which is at the head of Port Phillip.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Additional seaports are at Westernport, Geelong, and Portland.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] V/Line is a government-owned train and coach service provider in Victoria, providing inter-city services to a number of regional cities in the state.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria's major utilities include a collection of brown-coal-fired power stations, particularly in the Latrobe Valley.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] One of these was the recently decommissioned Hazelwood Power Station, which was number 1 on the worldwide List of least carbon efficient power stations.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The Victorian government is aiming to cut 40.6 megatonnes of greenhouse gas emissions by 2025.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria's water infrastructure includes a series of dams and reservoirs, predominantly in Central Victoria, that hold and collect water for much of the state.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The water collected is of a very high quality and requires little chlorination treatment, giving the water a taste more like water collected in a rainwater tank.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] In regional areas however, such as in the west of the state, chlorination levels are much higher.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The Victorian Water Grid consists of a number of new connections and pipelines being built across the State.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] This allows water to be moved around Victoria to where it is needed most and reduces the impact of localised droughts in an era thought to be influenced by climate change.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Major projects already completed as part of the Grid include the Wimmera Mallee Pipeline and the Goldfields Superpipe.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria is the home of Australian rules football, with ten of the 18 Australian Football League (AFL) clubs based in the state.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The AFL Grand Final is traditionally held at the Melbourne Cricket Ground on the last Saturday of September.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The state has a public holiday the day before the Grand Final, which coincides with the AFL Grand Final parade.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The MCG is sometimes called the spiritual home of Australian rules football.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The Victorian cricket team play in the national Sheffield Shield cricket competition.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria is represented in the National Rugby League by the Melbourne Storm.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Prior to their axing at the end of the 2024 season, Victoria was represented by the Melbourne Rebels in the Super Rugby.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] It is represented in the National Basketball League by Melbourne United and South East Melbourne Phoenix.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] It is also represented in soccer by Melbourne Victory, Melbourne City and Western United in the A-League.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Melbourne has held the 1956 Summer Olympics, 2006 Commonwealth Games and the FINA World Swimming Championship.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Melbourne is also home to the Australian Open tennis tournament in January each year, which is the first of the world's four Grand Slam tennis tournaments, as well as the Formula One Australian Grand Prix, which is, on an annual basis, usually held in March or April.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] It hosted the Australian Masters golf tournament from 1979 to 2015.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria's Bells Beach hosts one of the world's longest-running surfing competition, the Bells Beach SurfClassic, which is part of The ASP World Tour.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The Melbourne Vixens and Melbourne Mavericks represent Victoria in the Super Netball league.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Australia's most prestigious footrace, the Stawell Gift, is an annual event.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria is also home to the Aussie Millions poker tournament, the tournament with the highest potential proceeds in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The main horse racing tracks in Victoria are Caulfield Racecourse, Flemington Racecourse and Sandown Racecourse.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The Melbourne Spring Racing Carnival is one of the biggest horse racing events in the world and is one of the world's largest sporting events.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] The main race is for the $6 million Melbourne Cup, and crowds for the carnival usually exceed 700,000.
[src:blockade-novel/victoria-australia-p02] Victoria was due to host the 2026 Commonwealth Games but withdrew on 18 July 2023 as a result of increased costs of holding the event.
